  <section id="root-cause-1">
    <h2>Root Cause 1: Knowledge Base Rot</h2>

    <p>The most common reason chatbots give wrong answers is that their training data is out of date. This is not a FastBots-specific problem — it is a universal challenge for any chatbot that relies on uploaded content <strong>Verified</strong>.</p>

    <h3>How Knowledge Bases Decay</h3>

    <p>Chatbot knowledge bases decay as business data changes. Pricing updates, product specification changes, and policy revisions render uploaded content stale. Industry sources identify "stale content" as a top cause of chatbot inaccuracy <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>. HappySupport further notes that knowledge base structure "determines retrieval quality more than model choice" — and stale content degrades both retrieval quality and response accuracy <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>.</p>

    <h3>FastBots' Automated Retraining Feature</h3>

    <p>FastBots offers an automated retraining feature designed to address this. According to their website: "If you run an e-commerce store and adjust product prices, our system will automatically revisit your pages and update the chatbot with any changes it finds" <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. However, there are two important caveats.</p>

    <p>First, the automated retraining feature is gated behind the Business plan ($75/mo) <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. Users on the Free plan ($0/mo) or Essential plan ($24/mo) must update their knowledge base manually. Second, the effectiveness of this feature has not been independently verified — it exists and is described on the website, but no third-party testing confirms how well it detects and propagates content changes <strong>Unverified</strong>.</p>

    <h3>What You Can Upload (and Why That Is Not Enough)</h3>

    <p>FastBots accepts training data from websites (via crawler), uploaded documents (PDF, DOCX, TXT, CSV, XLS), Google Sheets, and YouTube video URLs. The crawler handles JavaScript-rendered sites and firewall-protected content. Training data limits range from 1 million characters (Free plan) to 25 million characters (Reseller plan) per bot <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>.</p>

    <p>The key insight: ingestion does not equal accurate retrieval. FastBots offers multiple data ingestion paths, but the platform's ability to retrieve the right content depends on how that content is structured — which is the subject of Root Cause 2.</p>

    <Callout type="warn">
      <strong>What to do about it:</strong> If your chatbot is giving answers based on old pricing, discontinued products, or outdated policies, the fix is almost certainly knowledge base rot. Review your training data freshness, set a manual update cadence if you are on the Free or Essential plan, and consider whether the Business plan's automated retraining justifies the upgrade cost.
    </Callout>
  </section>

  <section id="root-cause-2">
    <h2>Root Cause 2: RAG Retrieval Gaps</h2>

    <p>Even with perfectly fresh content, your FastBots chatbot can still give wrong answers if its retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) pipeline cannot find the right information. This is the most technical root cause — and the one users most often misinterpret as a model quality problem.</p>

    <h3>Why Document Structure Matters More Than Model Choice</h3>

    <p>For RAG-based chatbots, knowledge base structure has a greater impact on retrieval accuracy than the choice of LLM or prompt engineering <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>. A focused set of 15-20 well-structured articles outperforms 200 loosely organised PDFs <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>. Single-topic chunking — where each document covers exactly one task or question — significantly improves retrieval accuracy <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>. What works for human readers (long articles with anecdotes and context) can confuse AI agents <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>.</p>

    <p>The single highest-impact change you can make is adopting an answer-first structure: place the direct answer in the first 40-60 words, then add steps, then provide context <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>.</p>

    <h3>The Chunking Problem</h3>

    <p>Chunking strategy — how documents are split into retrievable pieces — is the single most impactful hyperparameter in RAG pipeline performance <strong>Verified</strong>. Getting chunk size wrong by one bracket degrades context precision by 15-30% <strong>Verified</strong>. Industry consensus recommends 400-800 token chunks with 10-20% overlap for production RAG systems <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>. Semantic chunking (variable-size chunks based on content boundaries) outperforms fixed-size chunking by 15-25% in retrieval accuracy, though it costs 3-5x more computationally <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>. Document-aware chunking improves domain-specific accuracy by 40% or more <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>.</p>

    <Callout type="warn">
      <strong>The no-code paradox:</strong> FastBots abstracts away all RAG configuration — users upload documents and the platform handles chunking, embedding, and retrieval internally. Users cannot adjust chunk size, overlap percentage, retrieval strategy, or embedding model <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. FastBots' own comparison blog notes the platform has "no RAG metrics — cannot track retrieval precision or recall" <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. This means users must optimise their source documents because they cannot tune the retrieval pipeline.
    </Callout>

    <h3>FastBots' Internal RAG Implementation</h3>

    <p>FastBots does not publicly document its chunking strategy, embedding model, or retrieval algorithm <strong>Verified</strong>. The platform is closed-source and abstracts all RAG configuration. Because FastBots does not expose chunking configuration, general RAG benchmarks (400-800 tokens with 20% overlap) describe the general principle rather than a FastBots-specific setting. However, the underlying principle applies to any RAG system: if your source documents are poorly structured, retrieval will fail regardless of the model you select.</p>

    <Callout type="info">
      <strong>What to do about it:</strong> Restructure your knowledge base around single-topic, answer-first documents. Each article should cover exactly one task or question. Place the direct answer in the first 40-60 words. Use consistent terminology throughout. A well-structured set of 15-20 focused documents will almost certainly outperform 200 loosely organised PDFs — and this fix costs nothing but time.
    </Callout>
  </section>

