  <section id="root-cause-3">
    <h2>Root Cause 3: Model Variance</h2>

    <p>FastBots offers 15+ AI models from three providers <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. If you have tried different models and seen different accuracy levels, you are not imagining it — model choice directly affects answer quality.</p>

    <h3>The FastBots Model Lineup</h3>

    <p>FastBots offers models from OpenAI (GPT-4o, GPT-4.1, GPT-5 series, o3), Anthropic (Claude 4 Sonnet, Claude 3.5 Haiku), and Google (Gemini 2.0 Flash, 2.5 Flash, 2.5 Pro). Models consume 1-10 message credits per response. Standard models (GPT-5 Mini, Gemini 2.5 Flash) use 1 credit; advanced models (GPT-4o, GPT-5, Claude 4 Sonnet) use 5-10 credits <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>.</p>

    <p>The Free plan restricts users to "basic LLMs (GPT-4o Mini and Gemini Flash 2.0)" <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. Paid plans ($24/mo Essential and above) unlock the full model selection. This is significant because free-tier models are less capable and more prone to hallucination <strong>Verified</strong>.</p>

    <Callout type="warn">
      <strong>Important note:</strong> FastBots does not publish per-model accuracy data for its platform <strong>Verified</strong>. However, general LLM benchmarks show that paid-tier models (GPT-5, Claude 4 Sonnet) produce fewer hallucinations than free-tier models (GPT-4o Mini, Gemini Flash). The credit-based pricing (1 credit vs 5-10 credits per response) serves as a proxy for model capability tiering. FastBots publishes no guidance on which model to choose for which use case, so model selection guidance must come from general LLM best practices.
    </Callout>

    <h3>Hallucination Is an Unsolved Problem</h3>

    <p>Even the most advanced models hallucinate. AI hallucinations remain an unsolved problem in 2026. Carnegie Mellon research published in <em>Memory & Cognition</em> (2025) found that LLMs "tended to get more overconfident even when they didn't do so well" <strong>Verified</strong>. OpenAI acknowledged in a September 2025 blog post that "hallucinations persist partly because current evaluation methods set the wrong incentives" and that "most evaluations measure model performance in a way that encourages guessing rather than honesty about uncertainty" <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. Duke University Libraries notes that "LLMs are trained to produce the most statistically likely answer, not to assess their own confidence" <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>.</p>

    <p>User testing has documented GPT-5 producing "wrong information on basic facts over half the time" in some scenarios <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>, though OpenAI claims GPT-5 produces "significantly fewer" hallucinations than predecessors. The critical point: switching to a more advanced model reduces but does not eliminate wrong answers.</p>

    <Callout type="info">
      <strong>What to do about it:</strong> If you are on the Free plan, upgrading to a paid plan unlocks better models — but this will not fix wrong answers caused by knowledge base rot or poor document structure. Upgrade the model after you have confirmed your knowledge base is fresh and well-structured. If you are already on a paid plan with a premium model (GPT-5, Claude 4 Sonnet) and still getting wrong answers, the root cause is almost certainly one of the other two factors.
    </Callout>
  </section>

  <section id="fix-vs-switch">
    <h2>When to Fix vs When to Switch</h2>

    <p>Not every accuracy problem can be fixed within FastBots. Some use cases are structurally unsuitable for the platform. Here is an honest assessment of when to invest in fixes and when to consider switching to a different chatbot platform.</p>

    <h3>Fix Within FastBots If:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Your knowledge base needs restructuring.</strong> As established in Root Cause 2, restructuring existing content into single-topic, answer-first documents is the highest-impact fix available, and it works on any FastBots plan <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Your content changes infrequently.</strong> If you update pricing or policies once a quarter, manual retraining on the Free or Essential plan is manageable.</li>
      <li><strong>You are on the Free plan using basic models.</strong> Upgrading to Essential ($24/mo) or Business ($75/mo) unlocks better models and more training data capacity <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Your accuracy issues follow a pattern.</strong> If the chatbot gets some answers wrong but others right, the problem is likely in specific documents rather than the platform itself.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Consider Switching Platforms If:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>You operate in a regulated industry.</strong> FastBots does not hold its own SOC 2 Type II certification. The platform's FAQ states "both platforms used to store your data are SOC2 and GDPR compliant," but this refers to infrastructure partners (Pinecone, AWS, Supabase), not FastBots itself <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. FastBots' own comparison blog confirms: "Is FastBots SOC 2 compliant? No" <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. This makes FastBots unsuitable for healthcare, finance, or legal applications that require independent SOC 2 attestation <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>You need HIPAA compliance.</strong> Nudge Security's security profile lists HIPAA as "Compliant" but this is not independently verified <strong>Unverified</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Your content changes daily.</strong> If your knowledge base requires constant updates, manual retraining becomes impractical, and the Business plan's automated retraining ($75/mo) has not been independently verified for effectiveness <strong>Unverified</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>You need retrieval analytics.</strong> FastBots provides no RAG metrics — you cannot track retrieval precision or recall <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. If you need to measure and optimise retrieval performance, platforms like Chatbase (SOC 2 Type II certified, native AI actions, $40-$500/mo) offer more transparency <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>.</li>
    </ul>

    <Callout type="info">
      <strong>Balanced perspective:</strong> FastBots is a legitimate platform for appropriate use cases — structured knowledge bases with stable content, standard customer support, and non-regulated industries. The platform offers 15+ models, multi-channel support (WhatsApp, Telegram, Instagram, Facebook, Slack natively), and pricing from $0 to $399/mo <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. The limitations documented in this section are honest caveats for specific high-stakes use cases, not a judgment on the platform overall.
    </Callout>
  </section>

  <section id="action-plan">
    <h2>Your Action Plan: Step-by-Step Diagnostic</h2>

    <p>When your FastBots chatbot gives a wrong answer, follow these diagnostic steps in order. Each step isolates one of the three root causes and tells you exactly what to fix.</p>

    <div>
      <h3>1. Audit Five Failed Conversations</h3>
      <p>Review five real conversations where the chatbot gave a wrong answer. For each one, label the failure type <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Missing source:</strong> The correct information does not exist in your knowledge base at all.</li>
        <li><strong>Wrong source:</strong> The chatbot retrieved a document but it was the wrong one — or the right document is structured poorly.</li>
        <li><strong>Should-have-escalated:</strong> The chatbot should have admitted uncertainty or escalated to a human but instead guessed.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If most failures are "missing source," you have a knowledge base coverage problem — add the missing information. If most are "wrong source," you have a RAG retrieval problem — restructure your documents. If most are "should-have-escalated," you have a model or prompting issue.</p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>2. Check Your Content Freshness</h3>
      <p>Review the last update date of every document in your knowledge base. If any content references old pricing, discontinued products, or outdated policies, update it immediately. If you are on the Free or Essential plan, set a recurring calendar reminder for manual updates based on how often your business data changes. If content freshness is a chronic problem, evaluate whether the Business plan's automated retraining ($75/mo) is worth the cost.</p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>3. Restructure One Document as an Experiment</h3>
      <p>Pick one document that consistently produces wrong answers. Rewrite it following the answer-first structure: direct answer in 40-60 words, then steps, then context. Ensure it covers exactly one topic or question. Upload the rewritten version and test the same queries. If accuracy improves, apply the same structure to your entire knowledge base.</p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>4. Test a Different Model</h3>
      <p>If you are on the Free plan, upgrade to at least Essential ($24/mo) to access better models <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. Switch your chatbot to GPT-5 or Claude 4 Sonnet (5-10 credits per response) and test the same queries that produced wrong answers. If accuracy improves, model variance was a contributing factor. If accuracy does not improve, the root cause is in your knowledge base or document structure — and switching models again will not help.</p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>5. Reduce Creativity and Add Guardrails</h3>
      <p>In your FastBots AI settings, lower the creativity/temperature setting and add explicit instructions to avoid guessing. Industry guidance recommends tighter approved sources, anti-guessing rules, and lower creativity as quick fixes for wrong-answer problems <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>. Add a fallback response such as: "I cannot find this information in my knowledge base. Please rephrase your question or contact support."</p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>6. Measure, Then Repeat</h3>
      <p>After implementing fixes, track whether wrong-answer rates decrease. Because FastBots does not provide RAG metrics or retrieval analytics <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>, you will need to manually sample conversations or use a third-party analytics tool. Run the five-conversation audit again after two weeks. If accuracy is still unacceptable and you have exhausted all three root causes, consider whether your use case requires a platform with SOC 2 Type II certification, retrieval analytics, or HIPAA compliance.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

