    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <FaqItem question="Does upgrading to a more expensive FastBots plan fix wrong answers?">
      <p>It depends on the root cause. Upgrading from Free to Essential ($24/mo) unlocks better models, which reduces hallucination risk if model variance was the problem <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. However, if the root cause is stale content (knowledge base rot) or poor document structure (RAG retrieval gaps), a model upgrade will not fix it. The diagnostic steps above will help you determine which root cause you have before spending money on an upgrade. FastBots also offers a free plan with 50 messages per month for testing <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>.</p>
    </FaqItem>

    <FaqItem question="Can I adjust how FastBots chunks my documents?">
      <p>No. FastBots abstracts away all RAG configuration — users cannot adjust chunk size, overlap percentage, retrieval strategy, or embedding model <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. This is by design as a no-code platform. The platform does not expose any RAG metrics, so you cannot track retrieval precision or recall <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. Your only lever for improving retrieval is restructuring your source documents to work well with however FastBots handles chunking internally. Industry research shows that well-structured, single-topic documents improve retrieval accuracy regardless of the underlying RAG implementation <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>.</p>
    </FaqItem>

    <FaqItem question="Which FastBots model is least likely to hallucinate?">
      <p>FastBots does not publish per-model accuracy data, so there is no definitive answer for the platform specifically. However, general LLM benchmarks consistently rank GPT-5 and Claude 4 Sonnet as the most capable models available on FastBots, consuming 5-10 credits per response compared to 1 credit for standard models <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. These premium models produce fewer hallucinations than the free-tier models (GPT-4o Mini, Gemini Flash 2.0). The credit-based pricing serves as a proxy for model capability tiering, but no FastBots-specific accuracy benchmarks exist to compare model performance within the platform <strong>Verified</strong>.</p>
    </FaqItem>

    <FaqItem question="Is FastBots suitable for my healthcare or finance chatbot?">
      <p>Likely not. FastBots does not hold its own SOC 2 Type II certification <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. The platform's FAQ states its data storage infrastructure is SOC 2 and GDPR compliant, but this refers to third-party providers (Pinecone, AWS, Supabase), not FastBots itself <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. HIPAA compliance status is listed as "Compliant" by Nudge Security but is not independently verified <strong>Unverified</strong>. For regulated industries requiring independent SOC 2 attestation or HIPAA certification, platforms like Chatbase (which holds SOC 2 Type II certification) may be more appropriate <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>.</p>
    </FaqItem>

    <FaqItem question="Can I use my own custom GPT model with FastBots?">
      <p>No. FastBots offers 15+ models from OpenAI, Anthropic, and Google, but users cannot bring their own custom model or fine-tune existing models <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. Model selection is limited to the pre-integrated options on each pricing tier. The Free plan restricts users to "basic LLMs (GPT-4o Mini and Gemini Flash 2.0)," while paid plans unlock the full lineup including GPT-5 and Claude 4 Sonnet <strong>Vendor Claim</strong>. If you need custom model training or fine-tuning, FastBots is not the right platform.</p>
    </FaqItem>

    <FaqItem question="How do I know if my chatbot's wrong answer is caused by RAG retrieval or model hallucination?">
      <p>The diagnostic method recommended by industry guides is to review the failed conversation and determine whether the correct information exists in your knowledge base but was not retrieved correctly (RAG retrieval gap) or the chatbot invented an answer that does not exist in your knowledge base (model hallucination) <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>. If the wrong answer sounds plausible and is vaguely related to your content, it is likely a retrieval gap — the chatbot found a partially relevant but incorrect document. If the wrong answer is confidently stated but clearly made up (e.g., a price that was never a price, an invented product feature), it is likely a hallucination — the model generated content not grounded in your documents. Try lowering creativity settings and adding anti-guessing rules as a first step <strong>Third-Party Reported</strong>.</p>
    </FaqItem>
